<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Quad" class="currentChild" href="Quad">Quad</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
When used as a verb, <em>quad</em> means, in typography and typesetting, to space out the blank portion of a line to its full measure. See <a title="Quadding" href="Quadding">Quadding</a>. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
When used as a noun, <em>quad</em> means, in metal typography, a blank piece of metal—more formally called a <em>quadrat</em>—used to fill up a line of type, forcing the rest of the characters into a desired position on the line. Quads were used to set a line <a title="Flush Left" href="Flush_Left">flush left</a>, <a title="Flush Right" href="Flush_Right">flush right</a>, or centered. 
</p>
<p id="l5">
In <a title="Binding and Finishing" href="Binding_and_Finishing">binding and finishing</a>, the term <em>quad</em> is also a shorthand term for a <a title="Quadruple" href="Quadruple">quadruple</a> folder. See <a title="Folding: Knife Folder" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/Folding:_Knife_Folder">Folding: Knife Folder</a>. 
</p>
